{"type":"message","id":"a582d9b8","parentId":"275b46a6","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:50:47.207Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9bp3v6q43qu3_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:summary: \"OpenClaw tools and plugins overview: what the agent can do and how to extend it\"\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Everything the agent does beyond generating text happens through **tools**.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Tools are how the agent reads files, runs commands, browses the web, sends\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:  <Step title=\"Tools are what the agent calls\">\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    A tool is a typed function the agent can invoke (e.g. `exec`, `browser`,\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    The agent sees tools as structured function definitions sent to the model API.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:  <Step title=\"Skills teach the agent when and how\">\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    Skills give the agent context, constraints, and step-by-step guidance for\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `message`                    | Send messages across all channels                        | [Agent Send](/tools/agent-send)   |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `sessions_*` / `agents_list` | Session management, sub-agents                           | [Sub-agents](/tools/subagents)    |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Control which tools the agent can call via `tools.allow` / `tools.deny` in\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Per-agent override: `agents.list[].tools.profile`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `minimal`   | `session_status` only                       |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `group:sessions`   | sessions_list, sessions_history, sessions_send, sessions_spawn, session_status |"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":19,"aggregated":"/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:summary: \"OpenClaw tools and plugins overview: what the agent can do and how to extend it\"\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Everything the agent does beyond generating text happens through **tools**.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Tools are how the agent reads files, runs commands, browses the web, sends\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:  <Step title=\"Tools are what the agent calls\">\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    A tool is a typed function the agent can invoke (e.g. `exec`, `browser`,\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    The agent sees tools as structured function definitions sent to the model API.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:  <Step title=\"Skills teach the agent when and how\">\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:    Skills give the agent context, constraints, and step-by-step guidance for\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `message`                    | Send messages across all channels                        | [Agent Send](/tools/agent-send)   |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `sessions_*` / `agents_list` | Session management, sub-agents                           | [Sub-agents](/tools/subagents)    |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Control which tools the agent can call via `tools.allow` / `tools.deny` in\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:Per-agent override: `agents.list[].tools.profile`.\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `minimal`   | `session_status` only                       |\n/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/index.md:| `group:sessions`   | sessions_list, sessions_history, sessions_send, sessions_spawn, session_status |","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-cody"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774309847204}}
{"type":"message","id":"3ac744a8","parentId":"a582d9b8","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:50:47.210Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9bp3v6q43qu3_2","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"OpenClaw tools and plugins overview: what the agent can do and how to extend it\"\nread_when:\n  - You want to understand what tools OpenClaw provides\n  - You need to configure, allow, or deny tools\n  - You are deciding between built-in tools, skills, and plugins\ntitle: \"Tools and Plugins\"\n---\n\n# Tools and Plugins\n\nEverything the agent does beyond generating text happens through **tools**.\nTools are how the agent reads files, runs commands, browses the web, sends\nmessages, and interacts with devices.\n\n## Tools, skills, and plugins\n\nOpenClaw has three layers that work together:\n\n<Steps>\n  <Step title=\"Tools are what the agent calls\">\n    A tool is a typed function the agent can invoke (e.g. `exec`, `browser`,\n    `web_search`, `message`). OpenClaw ships a set of **built-in tools** and\n    plugins can register additional ones.\n\n    The agent sees tools as structured function definitions sent to the model API.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Skills teach the agent when and how\">\n    A skill is a markdown file (`SKILL.md`) injected into the system prompt.\n    Skills give the agent context, constraints, and step-by-step guidance for\n    using tools effectively. Skills live in your workspace, in shared folders,\n    or ship inside plugins.\n\n    [Skills reference](/tools/skills) | [Creating skills](/tools/creating-skills)\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Plugins package everything together\">\n    A plugin is a package that can register any combination of capabilities:\n    channels, model providers, tools, skills, speech, image generation, and more.\n    Some plugins are **core** (shipped with OpenClaw), others are **external**\n    (published on npm by the community).\n\n    [Install and configure plugins](/tools/plugin) | [Build your own](/plugins/building-plugins)\n\n  </Step>\n</Steps>\n\n## Built-in tools\n\nThese tools ship with OpenClaw and are available without installing any plugins:\n\n| Tool                         | What it does                                             | Page                              |\n| ---------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n| `exec` / `process`           | Run shell commands, manage background processes          | [Exec](/tools/exec)               |\n| `browser`                    | Control a Chromium browser (navigate, click, screenshot) | [Browser](/tools/browser)         |\n| `web_search` / `web_fetch`   | Search the web, fetch page content                       | [Web](/tools/web)                 |\n| `read` / `write` / `edit`    | File I/O in the workspace                                |                                   |\n| `apply_patch`                | Multi-hunk file patches                                  | [Apply Patch](/tools/apply-patch) |\n| `message`                    | Send messages across all channels                        | [Agent Send](/tools/agent-send)   |\n| `canvas`                     | Drive node Canvas (present, eval, snapshot)              |                                   |\n| `nodes`                      | Discover and target paired devices                       |                                   |\n| `cron` / `gateway`           | Manage scheduled jobs, restart gateway                   |                                   |\n| `image` / `image_generate`   | Analyze or generate images                               |                                   |\n| `sessions_*` / `agents_list` | Session management, sub-agents                           | [Sub-agents](/tools/subagents)    |\n\nFor image work, use `image` for analysis and `image_generate` for generation or editing. If you target `openai/*`, `google/*`, `fal/*`, or another non-default image provider, configure that provider's auth/API key first.\n\n### Plugin-provided tools\n\nPlugins can register additional tools. Some examples:\n\n- [Lobster](/tools/lobster) — typed workflow runtime with resumable approvals\n- [LLM Task](/tools/llm-task) — JSON-only LLM step for structured output\n- [Diffs](/tools/diffs) — diff viewer and renderer\n- [OpenProse](/prose) — markdown-first workflow orchestration\n\n## Tool configuration\n\n### Allow and deny lists\n\nControl which tools the agent can call via `tools.allow` / `tools.deny` in\nconfig. Deny always wins over allow.\n\n```json5\n{\n  tools: {\n    allow: [\"group:fs\", \"browser\", \"web_search\"],\n    deny: [\"exec\"],\n  },\n}\n```\n\n### Tool profiles\n\n`tools.profile` sets a base allowlist before `allow`/`deny` is applied.\nPer-agent override: `agents.list[].tools.profile`.\n\n| Profile     | What it includes                            |\n| ----------- | ------------------------------------------- |\n| `full`      | All tools (default)                         |\n| `coding`    | File I/O, runtime, sessions, memory, image  |\n| `messaging` | Messaging, session list/history/send/status |\n| `minimal`   | `session_status` only                       |\n\n### Tool groups\n\nUse `group:*` shorthands in allow/deny lists:\n\n| Group              | Tools                                                                          |\n| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n| `group:runtime`    | exec, bash, process                                                            |\n| `group:fs`         | read, write, edit, apply_patch                                                 |\n| `group:sessions`   | sessions_list, sessions_history, sessions_send, sessions_spawn, session_status |\n| `group:memory`     | memory_search, memory_get                                                      |\n| `group:web`        | web_search, web_fetch                                                          |\n| `group:ui`         | browser, canvas                                                                |\n| `group:automation` | cron, gateway                                                                  |\n| `group:messaging`  | message                                                                        |\n| `group:nodes`      | nodes                                                                          |\n| `group:openclaw`   | All built-in OpenClaw tools (excludes plugin tools)                            |\n\n### Provider-specific restrictions\n\nUse `tools.byProvider` to restrict tools for specific providers without\nchanging global defaults:\n\n```json5\n{\n  tools: {\n    profile: \"coding\",\n    byProvider: {\n      \"google-antigravity\": { profile: \"minimal\" },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":19,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"OpenClaw tools and plugins overview: what the agent can do and how to extend it\"\nread_when:\n  - You want to understand what tools OpenClaw provides\n  - You need to configure, allow, or deny tools\n  - You are deciding between built-in tools, skills, and plugins\ntitle: \"Tools and Plugins\"\n---\n\n# Tools and Plugins\n\nEverything the agent does beyond generating text happens through **tools**.\nTools are how the agent reads files, runs commands, browses the web, sends\nmessages, and interacts with devices.\n\n## Tools, skills, and plugins\n\nOpenClaw has three layers that work together:\n\n<Steps>\n  <Step title=\"Tools are what the agent calls\">\n    A tool is a typed function the agent can invoke (e.g. `exec`, `browser`,\n    `web_search`, `message`). OpenClaw ships a set of **built-in tools** and\n    plugins can register additional ones.\n\n    The agent sees tools as structured function definitions sent to the model API.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Skills teach the agent when and how\">\n    A skill is a markdown file (`SKILL.md`) injected into the system prompt.\n    Skills give the agent context, constraints, and step-by-step guidance for\n    using tools effectively. Skills live in your workspace, in shared folders,\n    or ship inside plugins.\n\n    [Skills reference](/tools/skills) | [Creating skills](/tools/creating-skills)\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Plugins package everything together\">\n    A plugin is a package that can register any combination of capabilities:\n    channels, model providers, tools, skills, speech, image generation, and more.\n    Some plugins are **core** (shipped with OpenClaw), others are **external**\n    (published on npm by the community).\n\n    [Install and configure plugins](/tools/plugin) | [Build your own](/plugins/building-plugins)\n\n  </Step>\n</Steps>\n\n## Built-in tools\n\nThese tools ship with OpenClaw and are available without installing any plugins:\n\n| Tool                         | What it does                                             | Page                              |\n| ---------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n| `exec` / `process`           | Run shell commands, manage background processes          | [Exec](/tools/exec)               |\n| `browser`                    | Control a Chromium browser (navigate, click, screenshot) | [Browser](/tools/browser)         |\n| `web_search` / `web_fetch`   | Search the web, fetch page content                       | [Web](/tools/web)                 |\n| `read` / `write` / `edit`    | File I/O in the workspace                                |                                   |\n| `apply_patch`                | Multi-hunk file patches                                  | [Apply Patch](/tools/apply-patch) |\n| `message`                    | Send messages across all channels                        | [Agent Send](/tools/agent-send)   |\n| `canvas`                     | Drive node Canvas (present, eval, snapshot)              |                                   |\n| `nodes`                      | Discover and target paired devices                       |                                   |\n| `cron` / `gateway`           | Manage scheduled jobs, restart gateway                   |                                   |\n| `image` / `image_generate`   | Analyze or generate images                               |                                   |\n| `sessions_*` / `agents_list` | Session management, sub-agents                           | [Sub-agents](/tools/subagents)    |\n\nFor image work, use `image` for analysis and `image_generate` for generation or editing. If you target `openai/*`, `google/*`, `fal/*`, or another non-default image provider, configure that provider's auth/API key first.\n\n### Plugin-provided tools\n\nPlugins can register additional tools. Some examples:\n\n- [Lobster](/tools/lobster) — typed workflow runtime with resumable approvals\n- [LLM Task](/tools/llm-task) — JSON-only LLM step for structured output\n- [Diffs](/tools/diffs) — diff viewer and renderer\n- [OpenProse](/prose) — markdown-first workflow orchestration\n\n## Tool configuration\n\n### Allow and deny lists\n\nControl which tools the agent can call via `tools.allow` / `tools.deny` in\nconfig. Deny always wins over allow.\n\n```json5\n{\n  tools: {\n    allow: [\"group:fs\", \"browser\", \"web_search\"],\n    deny: [\"exec\"],\n  },\n}\n```\n\n### Tool profiles\n\n`tools.profile` sets a base allowlist before `allow`/`deny` is applied.\nPer-agent override: `agents.list[].tools.profile`.\n\n| Profile     | What it includes                            |\n| ----------- | ------------------------------------------- |\n| `full`      | All tools (default)                         |\n| `coding`    | File I/O, runtime, sessions, memory, image  |\n| `messaging` | Messaging, session list/history/send/status |\n| `minimal`   | `session_status` only                       |\n\n### Tool groups\n\nUse `group:*` shorthands in allow/deny lists:\n\n| Group              | Tools                                                                          |\n| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n| `group:runtime`    | exec, bash, process                                                            |\n| `group:fs`         | read, write, edit, apply_patch                                                 |\n| `group:sessions`   | sessions_list, sessions_history, sessions_send, sessions_spawn, session_status |\n| `group:memory`     | memory_search, memory_get                                                      |\n| `group:web`        | web_search, web_fetch                                                          |\n| `group:ui`         | browser, canvas                                                                |\n| `group:automation` | cron, gateway                                                                  |\n| `group:messaging`  | message                                                                        |\n| `group:nodes`      | nodes                                                                          |\n| `group:openclaw`   | All built-in OpenClaw tools (excludes plugin tools)                            |\n\n### Provider-specific restrictions\n\nUse `tools.byProvider` to restrict tools for specific providers without\nchanging global defaults:\n\n```json5\n{\n  tools: {\n    profile: \"coding\",\n    byProvider: {\n      \"google-antigravity\": { profile: \"minimal\" },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-cody"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774309847207}}
{"type":"message","id":"457f2fd2","parentId":"3ac744a8","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:50:50.856Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me understand what endpoints the gateway HTTP API exposes. Let me also check the web/control-ui.md which mentions `system-presence`.","thinkingSignature":"49197882244fa54bf97082dfc53a7f7c2ebbb5a8a13abf250cef6a2ef144f288"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e3zg5vi0p3k6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/web/control-ui.md | head -100"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e3zg5vi0p3k6_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/web/tui.md | head -80"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":15665,"output":111,"cacheRead":15940,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":31716,"cost":{"input":0.0046995,"output":0.00013319999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0009563999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005789099999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774309847211,"responseId":"061104d7943beb3fe30d946eb1e2a723"}}
{"type":"message","id":"dfbba066","parentId":"457f2fd2","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:50:50.892Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_e3zg5vi0p3k6_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"Browser-based control UI for the Gateway (chat, nodes, config)\"\nread_when:\n  - You want to operate the Gateway from a browser\n  - You want Tailnet access without SSH tunnels\ntitle: \"Control UI\"\n---\n\n# Control UI (browser)\n\nThe Control UI is a small **Vite + Lit** single-page app served by the Gateway:\n\n- default: `http://<host>:18789/`\n- optional prefix: set `gateway.controlUi.basePath` (e.g. `/openclaw`)\n\nIt speaks **directly to the Gateway WebSocket** on the same port.\n\n## Quick open (local)\n\nIf the Gateway is running on the same computer, open:\n\n- [http://127.0.0.1:18789/](http://127.0.0.1:18789/) (or [http://localhost:18789/](http://localhost:18789/))\n\nIf the page fails to load, start the Gateway first: `openclaw gateway`.\n\nAuth is supplied during the WebSocket handshake via:\n\n- `connect.params.auth.token`\n- `connect.params.auth.password`\n  The dashboard settings panel keeps a token for the current browser tab session and selected gateway URL; passwords are not persisted.\n  Onboarding generates a gateway token by default, so paste it here on first connect.\n\n## Device pairing (first connection)\n\nWhen you connect to the Control UI from a new browser or device, the Gateway\nrequires a **one-time pairing approval** — even if you're on the same Tailnet\nwith `gateway.auth.allowTailscale: true`. This is a security measure to prevent\nunauthorized access.\n\n**What you'll see:** \"disconnected (1008): pairing required\"\n\n**To approve the device:**\n\n```bash\n# List pending requests\nopenclaw devices list\n\n# Approve by request ID\nopenclaw devices approve <requestId>\n```\n\nIf the browser retries pairing with changed auth details (role/scopes/public\nkey), the previous pending request is superseded and a new `requestId` is\ncreated. Re-run `openclaw devices list` before approval.\n\nOnce approved, the device is remembered and won't require re-approval unless\nyou revoke it with `openclaw devices revoke --device <id> --role <role>`. See\n[Devices CLI](/cli/devices) for token rotation and revocation.\n\n**Notes:**\n\n- Local connections (`127.0.0.1`) are auto-approved.\n- Remote connections (LAN, Tailnet, etc.) require explicit approval.\n- Each browser profile generates a unique device ID, so switching browsers or\n  clearing browser data will require re-pairing.\n\n## Language support\n\nThe Control UI can localize itself on first load based on your browser locale, and you can override it later from the language picker in the Access card.\n\n- Supported locales: `en`, `zh-CN`, `zh-TW`, `pt-BR`, `de`, `es`\n- Non-English translations are lazy-loaded in the browser.\n- The selected locale is saved in browser storage and reused on future visits.\n- Missing translation keys fall back to English.\n\n## What it can do (today)\n\n- Chat with the model via Gateway WS (`chat.history`, `chat.send`, `chat.abort`, `chat.inject`)\n- Stream tool calls + live tool output cards in Chat (agent events)\n- Channels: WhatsApp/Telegram/Discord/Slack + plugin channels (Mattermost, etc.) status + QR login + per-channel config (`channels.status`, `web.login.*`, `config.patch`)\n- Instances: presence list + refresh (`system-presence`)\n- Sessions: list + per-session thinking/fast/verbose/reasoning overrides (`sessions.list`, `sessions.patch`)\n- Cron jobs: list/add/edit/run/enable/disable + run history (`cron.*`)\n- Skills: status, enable/disable, install, API key updates (`skills.*`)\n- Nodes: list + caps (`node.list`)\n- Exec approvals: edit gateway or node allowlists + ask policy for `exec host=gateway/node` (`exec.approvals.*`)\n- Config: view/edit `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` (`config.get`, `config.set`)\n- Config: apply + restart with validation (`config.apply`) and wake the last active session\n- Config writes include a base-hash guard to prevent clobbering concurrent edits\n- Config schema + form rendering (`config.schema`, including plugin + channel schemas); Raw JSON editor remains available\n- Debug: status/health/models snapshots + event log + manual RPC calls (`status`, `health`, `models.list`)\n- Logs: live tail of gateway file logs with filter/export (`logs.tail`)\n- Update: run a package/git update + restart (`update.run`) with a restart report\n\nCron jobs panel notes:\n\n- For isolated jobs, delivery defaults to announce summary. You can switch to none if you want internal-only runs.\n- Channel/target fields appear when announce is selected.\n- Webhook mode uses `delivery.mode = \"webhook\"` with `delivery.to` set to a valid HTTP(S) webhook URL.\n- For main-session jobs, webhook and none delivery modes are available."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":19,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"Browser-based control UI for the Gateway (chat, nodes, config)\"\nread_when:\n  - You want to operate the Gateway from a browser\n  - You want Tailnet access without SSH tunnels\ntitle: \"Control UI\"\n---\n\n# Control UI (browser)\n\nThe Control UI is a small **Vite + Lit** single-page app served by the Gateway:\n\n- default: `http://<host>:18789/`\n- optional prefix: set `gateway.controlUi.basePath` (e.g. `/openclaw`)\n\nIt speaks **directly to the Gateway WebSocket** on the same port.\n\n## Quick open (local)\n\nIf the Gateway is running on the same computer, open:\n\n- [http://127.0.0.1:18789/](http://127.0.0.1:18789/) (or [http://localhost:18789/](http://localhost:18789/))\n\nIf the page fails to load, start the Gateway first: `openclaw gateway`.\n\nAuth is supplied during the WebSocket handshake via:\n\n- `connect.params.auth.token`\n- `connect.params.auth.password`\n  The dashboard settings panel keeps a token for the current browser tab session and selected gateway URL; passwords are not persisted.\n  Onboarding generates a gateway token by default, so paste it here on first connect.\n\n## Device pairing (first connection)\n\nWhen you connect to the Control UI from a new browser or device, the Gateway\nrequires a **one-time pairing approval** — even if you're on the same Tailnet\nwith `gateway.auth.allowTailscale: true`. This is a security measure to prevent\nunauthorized access.\n\n**What you'll see:** \"disconnected (1008): pairing required\"\n\n**To approve the device:**\n\n```bash\n# List pending requests\nopenclaw devices list\n\n# Approve by request ID\nopenclaw devices approve <requestId>\n```\n\nIf the browser retries pairing with changed auth details (role/scopes/public\nkey), the previous pending request is superseded and a new `requestId` is\ncreated. Re-run `openclaw devices list` before approval.\n\nOnce approved, the device is remembered and won't require re-approval unless\nyou revoke it with `openclaw devices revoke --device <id> --role <role>`. See\n[Devices CLI](/cli/devices) for token rotation and revocation.\n\n**Notes:**\n\n- Local connections (`127.0.0.1`) are auto-approved.\n- Remote connections (LAN, Tailnet, etc.) require explicit approval.\n- Each browser profile generates a unique device ID, so switching browsers or\n  clearing browser data will require re-pairing.\n\n## Language support\n\nThe Control UI can localize itself on first load based on your browser locale, and you can override it later from the language picker in the Access card.\n\n- Supported locales: `en`, `zh-CN`, `zh-TW`, `pt-BR`, `de`, `es`\n- Non-English translations are lazy-loaded in the browser.\n- The selected locale is saved in browser storage and reused on future visits.\n- Missing translation keys fall back to English.\n\n## What it can do (today)\n\n- Chat with the model via Gateway WS (`chat.history`, `chat.send`, `chat.abort`, `chat.inject`)\n- Stream tool calls + live tool output cards in Chat (agent events)\n- Channels: WhatsApp/Telegram/Discord/Slack + plugin channels (Mattermost, etc.) status + QR login + per-channel config (`channels.status`, `web.login.*`, `config.patch`)\n- Instances: presence list + refresh (`system-presence`)\n- Sessions: list + per-session thinking/fast/verbose/reasoning overrides (`sessions.list`, `sessions.patch`)\n- Cron jobs: list/add/edit/run/enable/disable + run history (`cron.*`)\n- Skills: status, enable/disable, install, API key updates (`skills.*`)\n- Nodes: list + caps (`node.list`)\n- Exec approvals: edit gateway or node allowlists + ask policy for `exec host=gateway/node` (`exec.approvals.*`)\n- Config: view/edit `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` (`config.get`, `config.set`)\n- Config: apply + restart with validation (`config.apply`) and wake the last active session\n- Config writes include a base-hash guard to prevent clobbering concurrent edits\n- Config schema + form rendering (`config.schema`, including plugin + channel schemas); Raw JSON editor remains available\n- Debug: status/health/models snapshots + event log + manual RPC calls (`status`, `health`, `models.list`)\n- Logs: live tail of gateway file logs with filter/export (`logs.tail`)\n- Update: run a package/git update + restart (`update.run`) with a restart report\n\nCron jobs panel notes:\n\n- For isolated jobs, delivery defaults to announce summary. You can switch to none if you want internal-only runs.\n- Channel/target fields appear when announce is selected.\n- Webhook mode uses `delivery.mode = \"webhook\"` with `delivery.to` set to a valid HTTP(S) webhook URL.\n- For main-session jobs, webhook and none delivery modes are available.","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-cody"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774309850889}}
{"type":"message","id":"305ea886","parentId":"dfbba066","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:50:50.895Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_e3zg5vi0p3k6_2","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"Terminal UI (TUI): connect to the Gateway from any machine\"\nread_when:\n  - You want a beginner-friendly walkthrough of the TUI\n  - You need the complete list of TUI features, commands, and shortcuts\ntitle: \"TUI\"\n---\n\n# TUI (Terminal UI)\n\n## Quick start\n\n1. Start the Gateway.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw gateway\n```\n\n2. Open the TUI.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw tui\n```\n\n3. Type a message and press Enter.\n\nRemote Gateway:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw tui --url ws://<host>:<port> --token <gateway-token>\n```\n\nUse `--password` if your Gateway uses password auth.\n\n## What you see\n\n- Header: connection URL, current agent, current session.\n- Chat log: user messages, assistant replies, system notices, tool cards.\n- Status line: connection/run state (connecting, running, streaming, idle, error).\n- Footer: connection state + agent + session + model + think/fast/verbose/reasoning + token counts + deliver.\n- Input: text editor with autocomplete.\n\n## Mental model: agents + sessions\n\n- Agents are unique slugs (e.g. `main`, `research`). The Gateway exposes the list.\n- Sessions belong to the current agent.\n- Session keys are stored as `agent:<agentId>:<sessionKey>`.\n  - If you type `/session main`, the TUI expands it to `agent:<currentAgent>:main`.\n  - If you type `/session agent:other:main`, you switch to that agent session explicitly.\n- Session scope:\n  - `per-sender` (default): each agent has many sessions.\n  - `global`: the TUI always uses the `global` session (the picker may be empty).\n- The current agent + session are always visible in the footer.\n\n## Sending + delivery\n\n- Messages are sent to the Gateway; delivery to providers is off by default.\n- Turn delivery on:\n  - `/deliver on`\n  - or the Settings panel\n  - or start with `openclaw tui --deliver`\n\n## Pickers + overlays\n\n- Model picker: list available models and set the session override.\n- Agent picker: choose a different agent.\n- Session picker: shows only sessions for the current agent.\n- Settings: toggle deliver, tool output expansion, and thinking visibility.\n\n## Keyboard shortcuts\n\n- Enter: send message\n- Esc: abort active run\n- Ctrl+C: clear input (press twice to exit)\n- Ctrl+D: exit\n- Ctrl+L: model picker\n- Ctrl+G: agent picker\n- Ctrl+P: session picker\n- Ctrl+O: toggle tool output expansion\n- Ctrl+T: toggle thinking visibility (reloads history)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":19,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"Terminal UI (TUI): connect to the Gateway from any machine\"\nread_when:\n  - You want a beginner-friendly walkthrough of the TUI\n  - You need the complete list of TUI features, commands, and shortcuts\ntitle: \"TUI\"\n---\n\n# TUI (Terminal UI)\n\n## Quick start\n\n1. Start the Gateway.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw gateway\n```\n\n2. Open the TUI.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw tui\n```\n\n3. Type a message and press Enter.\n\nRemote Gateway:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw tui --url ws://<host>:<port> --token <gateway-token>\n```\n\nUse `--password` if your Gateway uses password auth.\n\n## What you see\n\n- Header: connection URL, current agent, current session.\n- Chat log: user messages, assistant replies, system notices, tool cards.\n- Status line: connection/run state (connecting, running, streaming, idle, error).\n- Footer: connection state + agent + session + model + think/fast/verbose/reasoning + token counts + deliver.\n- Input: text editor with autocomplete.\n\n## Mental model: agents + sessions\n\n- Agents are unique slugs (e.g. `main`, `research`). The Gateway exposes the list.\n- Sessions belong to the current agent.\n- Session keys are stored as `agent:<agentId>:<sessionKey>`.\n  - If you type `/session main`, the TUI expands it to `agent:<currentAgent>:main`.\n  - If you type `/session agent:other:main`, you switch to that agent session explicitly.\n- Session scope:\n  - `per-sender` (default): each agent has many sessions.\n  - `global`: the TUI always uses the `global` session (the picker may be empty).\n- The current agent + session are always visible in the footer.\n\n## Sending + delivery\n\n- Messages are sent to the Gateway; delivery to providers is off by default.\n- Turn delivery on:\n  - `/deliver on`\n  - or the Settings panel\n  - or start with `openclaw tui --deliver`\n\n## Pickers + overlays\n\n- Model picker: list available models and set the session override.\n- Agent picker: choose a different agent.\n- Session picker: shows only sessions for the current agent.\n- Settings: toggle deliver, tool output expansion, and thinking visibility.\n\n## Keyboard shortcuts\n\n- Enter: send message\n- Esc: abort active run\n- Ctrl+C: clear input (press twice to exit)\n- Ctrl+D: exit\n- Ctrl+L: model picker\n- Ctrl+G: agent picker\n- Ctrl+P: session picker\n- Ctrl+O: toggle tool output expansion\n- Ctrl+T: toggle thinking visibility (reloads history)","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-cody"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774309850891}}
{"type":"message","id":"da414fcc","parentId":"305ea886","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:51:15.787Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the OpenClaw gateway API. The gateway exposes:\n\n1. WebSocket API at `ws://localhost:18789` with methods like:\n   - `system-presence` - list of system presence entries (nodes, instances)\n   - `sessions.list` / `sessions_list` - list sessions\n   - `chat.send` - send a message\n   - `chat.history` - get chat history\n\n2. HTTP API at `http://localhost:18789` with endpoints like:\n   - `POST /tools/invoke` - invoke tools like `sessions_list`, `session_status`\n\nLet me now start building the React app. First, I'll write the SPEC.md, then set up the project.\n\n\nI'll need to use the WebSocket connection for real-time agent status updates, though I should verify the exact auth requirements for the gateway and check if there's a token I need to pass along.\n\nFor the frontend, I'm thinking through the design: dark background with frosted glass cards for each agent, status indicators showing online/busy/offline states, a compose modal, header with title and datetime, and smooth animations throughout. I'll start by writing out the spec, then scaffold a Vite + React + TypeScript + Tailwind project in the specified directory.\n\nThe gateway connection will use WebSocket to pull agent data—I'm checking the OpenClaw docs to understand the protocol, particularly around the `system-presence` method and the `hello-ok` response that contains presence and health information. The connection flow starts with the client sending a `connect` request, so I need to understand that handshake before implementing the real-time updates.\n\nFor the HTTP API, I can use `/tools/invoke` with the `sessions_list` tool to fetch sessions, and the WebSocket subscription to `presence` events will give me live status updates. Since this is Bobby's personal dashboard running locally, I'll start without authentication and add it if needed.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the 9 agents with their identifiers and roles.\n\nFor the WebSocket connection, I need to understand the message format - it's JSON with request and response objects that include IDs, methods, and parameters. The gateway sends events asynchronously, so I'll need to handle those separately from direct responses.\n\nMy approach is to establish the connection with the proper handshake, then use `agent.list` to retrieve all available agents.\n\nFor agent status, the presence data from the system-presence call should tell me who's online, and the sessions_list tool will show me their current state. I don't see a direct message-sending method, but chat.send is what I need for that - it's exposed through the webchat interface.\n\nLet me start building this and adjust as needed based on what the gateway actually returns.\n\nI'll create the Vite project in the specified directory and write out a detailed spec first, then implement the WebSocket client to connect and see what data comes back.","thinkingSignature":"0a4104c1993c6e88b6bf03d09d6f08e2aa65293f1889e8804ab8b0f6e295344a"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough context on the OpenClaw gateway API. Let me build the project.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0sh79g5gj3x8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /Users/bobbygalletta/agent-mission-control && ls /Users/bobbygalletta/agent-mission-control/"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":17420,"output":666,"cacheRead":15940,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34026,"cost":{"input":0.005226,"output":0.0007991999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0009563999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.006981599999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774309850895,"responseId":"061104dba48488ef1566adf362ba6a36"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e530143a","parentId":"da414fcc","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:51:15.830Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0sh79g5gj3x8_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"(no output)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":28,"aggregated":"","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-cody"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774309875827}}
{"type":"message","id":"81011d98","parentId":"e530143a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:52:08.081Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, the directory is empty. Let me write the SPEC.md first, then scaffold the project.","thinkingSignature":"e38b6826d1337e1049a6cc9ec7a0f4709967d1b2177e998dee07423e6cdac020"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_05hkc8uu05rk_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Mission Control — AI Agent Dashboard\n\n## 1. Concept & Vision\n\nMission Control is Bobby's command center for his AI agent team — a sleek, real-time dashboard that feels like piloting a spacecraft from the future. Inspired by iOS 26's liquid glass aesthetic, every panel floats over a deep void, frosted and luminous. The experience should feel premium, ambient, and alive — not a static admin panel, but a living mission center where every agent's presence is felt.\n\n## 2. Design Language\n\n**Aesthetic Direction:** iOS 26 \"liquid glass\" — ultra-dark backgrounds, translucent panels with heavy backdrop-blur, subtle luminous borders, soft ambient glows. Think visionOS meets a space operations center.\n\n**Color Palette:**\n- Background: `#08080e` (near-void black)\n- Surface glass: `rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.04)` with `rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08)` border\n- Primary accent: `#6366f1` (indigo glow)\n- Secondary accent: `#8b5cf6` (violet)\n- Status green: `#22c55e`\n- Status yellow: `#eab308`\n- Status red: `#ef4444`\n- Status gray: `#6b7280`\n- Text primary: `#f1f5f9`\n- Text secondary: `#94a3b8`\n- Text muted: `#475569`\n\n**Typography:**\n- Primary: `Inter` (clean, modern sans-serif from Google Fonts)\n- Monospace accents: `JetBrains Mono` for timestamps and status codes\n- Fallback: `system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif`\n\n**Spatial System:**\n- Base unit: 4px\n- Card padding: 20px\n- Grid gap: 16px\n- Border radius: 16px (cards), 12px (buttons), 24px (modal)\n- Glass blur: `blur(20px)` saturation(180%)\n\n**Motion Philosophy:**\n- Entrance: opacity 0→1, translateY(8px)→0, 300ms ease-out, staggered 50ms per card\n- Hover: scale(1.02), glow intensifies, 200ms ease-out\n- Modal: scale(0.95)→1, opacity 0→1, 250ms cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1)\n- Status pulse: keyframe glow animation for online agents (subtle 2s infinite)\n- Backdrop: all glass panels share consistent blur + saturation\n\n**Visual Assets:**\n- Icons: Lucide React (consistent, minimal line icons)\n- Agent avatars: Large emoji characters (40px)\n- Status dots: 10px circles with glow matching status color\n- Decorative: subtle radial gradient orbs in background (indigo + violet, very low opacity)\n\n## 3. Layout & Structure\n\n**Header:**\n- Left: \"Mission Control\" title with subtle indigo glow\n- Right: Live date/time (updates every second), connection status indicator\n- Full-width, sticky, glass morphism with bottom border glow\n\n**Agent Grid:**\n- 3 columns on desktop (≥1024px), 2 on tablet (≥640px), 1 on mobile\n- CSS Grid with auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr)\n- Cards have equal height in rows\n- Subtle stagger animation on initial load\n\n**Compose Modal:**\n- Centered overlay with backdrop blur\n- Frosted glass panel, max-width 480px\n- Agent avatar + name header\n- Textarea for message input\n- Send + Cancel buttons\n- Close on backdrop click or Escape key\n\n**Background:**\n- Fixed radial gradient orbs (very subtle, 5% opacity)\n- No flat solid color — depth through gradient layers\n\n## 4. Features & Interactions\n\n**Agent Cards:**\n- Display: emoji avatar, agent name, role subtitle, status badge, last active time\n- Click → open compose modal for that agent\n- Hover: elevate with shadow glow, slight scale\n- Status indicator with colored glow dot + text label\n- Online: pulsing green glow\n- Busy: static amber glow\n- Error: static red glow\n- Offline: no glow, muted styling\n\n**Status Polling:**\n- Poll gateway every 5 seconds via HTTP `/tools/invoke` for sessions list\n- WebSocket connection for real-time presence updates (when available)\n- Show \"Connecting...\" skeleton state while loading initial data\n- Show \"Gateway Offline\" state when unreachable\n\n**Compose Modal:**\n- Pre-selects the clicked agent\n- Textarea auto-focuses on open\n- Enter to send (Cmd/Ctrl+Enter for newline)\n- Shows sending state with spinner on Send button\n- Success: toast notification \"Message sent to [Agent]\"\n- Error: inline error message \"Failed to send: [reason]\"\n- Close with X button, backdrop click, or Escape key\n\n**Error States:**\n- Gateway unreachable: full-panel overlay with retry button\n- Agent unreachable: card shows \"unreachable\" status\n- Message send failure: inline error in modal\n\n**Empty/Loading:**\n- Skeleton cards with shimmer animation while loading agents\n\n## 5. Component Inventory\n\n**`<Header />`**\n- States: connected (green dot), connecting (yellow dot), disconnected (red dot)\n- Date/time: `HH:mm:ss` time, `MMM DD, YYYY` date below\n- Glass morphism background, sticky\n\n**`<AgentCard />`**\n- Props: agent data (id, name, emoji, role, status, lastActive)\n- States: default, hover (elevated + glow), loading (skeleton)\n- Status badge: colored dot + label text\n- Click handler opens compose modal\n\n**`<StatusBadge status />`**\n- status: `online` | `busy` | `error` | `offline`\n- Colored dot with appropriate glow effect\n- Text label matching status\n\n**`<ComposeModal />`**\n- Props: agent, isOpen, onClose, onSend\n- States: idle, sending (button spinner), error (inline message)\n- Textarea with glass styling\n- Send button: primary indigo, disabled while empty or sending\n\n**`<ConnectionStatus />`**\n- Dot indicator + label\n- Updates from gateway health probe\n\n**`<SkeletonCard />`**\n- Shimmer animation placeholder\n- Matches AgentCard dimensions\n\n**`<Toast />`**\n- Slide-in notification for send success/failure\n- Auto-dismiss after 3 seconds\n- Types: success (green), error (red)\n\n## 6. Technical Approach\n\n**Framework:** Vite + React 18 + TypeScript\n\n**Styling:** Tailwind CSS v3 with custom configuration for glass effects, animations, and color palette\n\n**State Management:** React hooks (useState, useEffect, useCallback, useRef) — no external state library needed\n\n**HTTP Client:** Native `fetch` API\n\n**WebSocket:** Native WebSocket API with reconnection logic\n\n**Project Structure:**\n```\nsrc/\n  components/\n    Header.tsx\n    AgentCard.tsx\n    AgentGrid.tsx\n    ComposeModal.tsx\n    StatusBadge.tsx\n    SkeletonCard.tsx\n    Toast.tsx\n  hooks/\n    useGateway.ts        # WebSocket + HTTP gateway connection\n    useAgentStatus.ts   # Agent status polling\n    useTime.ts          # Live clock\n  lib/\n    gateway.ts          # Gateway API client (HTTP + WS)\n    types.ts            # TypeScript interfaces\n  App.tsx\n  main.tsx\n  index.css             # Tailwind directives + custom animations\n```\n\n**Gateway Integration:**\n- Gateway URL: `http://localhost:18789` (configurable via `VITE_GATEWAY_URL` env)\n- Auth: reads from `VITE_GATEWAY_TOKEN` env var (optional for local)\n- HTTP polling: `POST /tools/invoke` with `sessions_list` tool every 5s\n- WebSocket: connect to `ws://localhost:18789`, send `connect` handshake, subscribe to `presence` events\n- Fallback: if WebSocket fails, rely on HTTP polling only\n\n**Agent Registry:**\n```typescript\nconst AGENTS = [\n  { id: 'dean', name: 'Dean', emoji: '🤖', role: 'General Assistant' },\n  { id: 'emmy', name: 'Emmy', emoji: '🦋', role: 'Email Specialist' },\n  { id: 'x', name: 'Agent X', emoji: '⚡', role: 'Twitter Specialist' },\n  { id: 'finn', name: 'Finn', emoji: '🧊', role: 'Finance Specialist' },\n  { id: 'yoyos', name: 'YoYo', emoji: '🎥', role: 'YouTube Specialist' },\n  { id: 'rex', name: 'Rex', emoji: '🔍', role: 'Research Executive' },\n  { id: 'dj', name: 'DJ', emoji: '🎧', role: 'Music Specialist' },\n  { id: 'cody', name: 'Cody', emoji: '💻', role: 'Coding Expert' },\n  { id: 'martha', name: 'Martha', emoji: '🌿', role: 'Personal Assistant' },\n]\n```\n\n**API Design (gateway client):**\n- `gatewayHealth()` → `GET /health` or `POST /tools/invoke` with health tool\n- `listSessions()` → `POST /tools/invoke` with `sessions_list`\n- `sendMessage(agentId, message)` → WebSocket `chat.send` or HTTP tool invoke\n- `connectWS()` → establishes WebSocket, returns presence stream\n\n**Deployment:** Vercel (static SPA, `vercel.json` for SPA routing)\n","file_path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/agent-mission-control/SPEC.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":18104,"output":2156,"cacheRead":15940,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36200,"cost":{"input":0.0054312,"output":0.0025872,"cacheRead":0.0009563999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0089748}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774309875831,"responseId":"061104f3c85584f10a50e890c6af8a7b"}}
